Cut the @streaky bacon{10%rasher} into 1cm wide slices. Tear the @mozzarella{2} cheese into small pieces. Pop the #kettle{} on to boil.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #saucepan{} on a medium-high heat. Once hot, add the bacon slices. Stir and cook until browned and crispy, ~{3-4%minutes}. Add the @tomato purée{30%g} and @dried thyme{1}. Stir together and cook for ~{1%minute}. Add the @orzo{360%g} to your pan and stir again so it gets a good coating of all the other ingredients.

Next, add the boiling @water{300%ml} to the orzo along with the @vegetable stock pot{1}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot. Pour in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1} and @cherry tomatoes{1} and bring the mixture to the boil.

> TIP: You can break up the cherry tomatoes with a spoon if your kids are likely to pick them out!

Simmer until the liquid has been absorbed and the orzo is tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

> TIP: Stir frequently to ensure nothing sticks to the bottom of the pan. If the liquid is all absorbed before the orzo is cooked, add another splash of water and give it a couple more mins.

When the orzo is cooked, remove from the heat, add the mozzarella pieces and half the @grated hard Italian style cheese{80%g}. Stir together until the cheese has melted. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it.

> TIP: If the kids don't like spinach, serve the orzo now as it is!

Roughly chop the @baby spinach{1}, then pop it on top of the orzo. Put a lid on the pan so the spinach wilts ~{3-4%minutes}, then stir it in.

Serve your cheesy tomato orzo in bowls with the remaining hard Italian cheese sprinkled on top. Enjoy!